def rename_columns(dataframe):
    # Ottieni le colonne (dalla quarta in poi, che sono quelle orarie)
    date_columns = dataframe.columns[3:]
    
    # Create a list to store the new column names
    new_column_names = []
    
    for date_column in date_columns:
        # Extract the day and hour from the column name
        day_hour = pd.to_datetime(date_column).strftime('%d_%H')
        
        # Append the new column name to the list
        new_column_names.append(day_hour)
    
    # Ensure the number of new column names matches the number of original columns
    if len(new_column_names) == len(date_columns):
        # Create a dictionary for renaming
        rename_dict = dict(zip(date_columns, new_column_names))
        
        # Rename the columns in the DataFrame
        dataframe.rename(columns=rename_dict, inplace=True)
    
    return dataframe

In [48]:
#Plot for electricity
plt.figure(figsize=(25, 15))

for i,city in enumerate(cities, 1):
    plt.subplot(4, 1, i)

    for user in users:
        filtered_df = df[(df['Location'] == city) & (df['User'] == user) & (df['Need'] == 'Electricity')]
        plt.plot(range(1, 673), filtered_df.iloc[:, 3:].values.flatten(), label=f'User {user}')
    
    plt.xlabel('Hours')
    plt.ylabel('kWh')
    plt.ylim(0,3)
    plt.xlim(0,675)
    plt.title(f'Electricity Time Series for {city}')
    plt.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

In [8]:
#Creating Y for each house type
def extend_Y(demand,need):
    Y=pd.DataFrame()
    hours = ['h01','h02','h03','h04','h05','h06','h07','h08','h09','h10','h11','h12','h13','h14','h15','h16','h17','h18','h19','h20','h21','h22','h23','h24']
    days=['01','02','03','04','05','06','07','08','09','10','11','12','13','14']
    short_seasons=['wi','mc','mw','su']
    j=0
    i=1
    for s in range(4):
        for d in range(14):
            if d<7:
                for h in range(24):
                    Y.loc[j,'n_names']=need
                    Y.loc[j,'th_names']=f'{hours[h]}_{short_seasons[s]}{days[d]}'
                    Y.loc[j,'values']=demand.loc[i]
                    j+=1
                    i+=1
            else:
                for h in range(24):
                    Y.loc[j,'n_names']=need
                    Y.loc[j,'th_names']=f'{hours[h]}_{short_seasons[s]}{days[d]}'
                    Y.loc[j,'values']=Y.loc[j-24*7]['values']
                    j+=1
    Y.loc[j,'n_names']=need
    Y.loc[j,'th_names']='peak'
    Y.loc[j,'values']=0
    j+=1
    return Y
In [11]:
for l in ['A','B','C','D']:
    house=f'Milano_{l}'
    Y=pd.DataFrame()
    Y=extend_Y(demand[f'Electricity_{house}'],'EE')
    Ynull=Y.copy()
    Y = pd.concat([Y, extend_Y(demand[f'Hot Sanitary Water_{house}'],'Hot water')], ignore_index=True)
    Y = pd.concat([Y, extend_Y(demand[f'Heating_{house}'],'Heat')], ignore_index=True)
    Y = pd.concat([Y, extend_Y(demand[f'Cooling_{house}'],'Cooling')], ignore_index=True)
    Y = pd.concat([Y, extend_Y(demand[f'Cooking_{house}'],'Cooking')], ignore_index=True)
    Ynull['values']=0
    Ynull['n_names']='Natural Gas'
    Y = pd.concat([Y, Ynull], ignore_index=True)

    # Write new file
    Y.to_excel(f'{house}_Y.xlsx', index=False)
